So, for instance, in our meditation we've just been trying to look at impermanence.

17
00:03:21,378 --> 00:03:24,342
Well, if you said to anybody in the street, everything changes, they'd say, so what?

18
00:03:24,362 --> 00:03:26,384
Everything, quite obviously everything changes.

19
00:03:27,126 --> 00:03:31,451
But in the Buddha's understanding this change is quite radical.

20
00:03:31,651 --> 00:03:34,014
Everything actually disappears and reappears.

21
00:03:34,256 --> 00:03:37,179
It moves into potential and then into actual.

22
00:03:37,939 --> 00:03:40,623
And it's that, it's recognizing that there are

23
00:03:40,974 --> 00:03:46,539
There's death with every moment, every single moment just drops away and then it arises.

24
00:03:47,199 --> 00:03:53,145
And this obviously can be experienced, but what it shows us is a discontinuity.

25
00:03:53,385 --> 00:03:56,108
That's the point, the discontinuity.

26
00:03:56,127 --> 00:04:04,594
So, for instance, when you see yourself in the mirror, you recognize that this is the same person that you've always known for all your life.

27
00:04:06,697 --> 00:04:10,020
And you presume that it's the same sort of person, it's the same body.

28
00:04:10,539 --> 00:04:38,910
but we know that the body completely changed every seven years all the atoms are completely transferred but we don't see that, we don't see that at all and therefore we live in that sort of comfortable delusion that this is this is the body that I've had and that it isn't and that there's somehow, there's some stability to it so it's really when we get down to understanding these things then it brings us up against these real

29
00:04:39,228 --> 00:04:42,411
understanding of life as to how it rises and passes away.

30
00:04:42,831 --> 00:04:51,177
Now, the point about this right effort in meditation is that we have to be clear that our effort is not to see this.

31
00:04:51,678 --> 00:04:54,401
Our effort is to get into a position where this is seen.

32
00:04:56,242 --> 00:05:08,273
In other words, we're trying to get into that position of the objective observer, of that place within us like an observation post, and we're just watching.

33
00:05:08,708 --> 00:05:34,384
one of the examples that I tend to use is the twitcher so they hide, they're in a hide and they look out through this little window with their binoculars and they just watch the bird, they don't do anything to the bird this is the point, they don't do anything, they just watch and then they go away and write their best seller now that's what we're doing, we're trying to find this little hide within ourselves and we're just watching and what are we watching?

34
00:05:34,564 --> 00:05:37,769
we're watching our physicality, the body

35
00:05:37,935 --> 00:05:39,317
and how it manifests.

36
00:05:39,336 --> 00:05:41,379
We're watching the heart and how it manifests.

37
00:05:42,060 --> 00:05:43,622
And we're watching the mind and thoughts.

38
00:05:44,062 --> 00:05:46,985
And it's just in the watching that we come to know ourselves.

39
00:05:47,384 --> 00:05:48,326
You don't have to try.

40
00:05:48,605 --> 00:05:49,367
It's just the watching.

41
00:05:51,408 --> 00:06:01,759
Now, if you try too hard, you see, if something comes in which makes you strain, then there's something else coming into the equation.

42
00:06:02,339 --> 00:06:06,684
You're either trying to achieve something or trying to concentrate.

43
00:06:07,024 --> 00:06:07,605
That's a bad one.

44
00:06:08,293 --> 00:06:10,437
Concentration comes with relaxation.

45
00:06:12,418 --> 00:06:17,365
So there's a story of Sona, who was one of the monks during the Buddha's time.

46
00:06:18,026 --> 00:06:27,839
And he'd sort of given up, and he decided that he was going to leave the monastic life and go back to the ordinary lay life.

47
00:06:27,860 --> 00:06:29,442
And when the Buddha heard this, he went to see him.

48
00:06:29,461 --> 00:06:30,624
And this was the big problem.

49
00:06:30,663 --> 00:06:32,406
He was straining and straining.

50
00:06:32,425 --> 00:06:36,250
So he talked about tuning a string on a vina.

51
00:06:36,331 --> 00:06:37,692
So that's a bit like a guitar.

52
00:06:39,040 --> 00:06:43,384
It mustn't be too tight, or else you miss the note, and it can't be too slack.

53
00:06:43,404 --> 00:06:50,093
And it's just getting that ability to just get the right effort so that your attention is steady.

54
00:06:50,894 --> 00:06:51,014
See?

55
00:06:52,115 --> 00:06:55,680
If you find yourself getting tense, then immediately you pull back and relax.

56
00:06:56,120 --> 00:06:59,584
If you find you're falling asleep, you wake up and make an effort.

57
00:06:59,605 --> 00:07:00,365
See?

58
00:07:00,386 --> 00:07:07,574
And that moment of being relaxed and yet firm is very difficult for us, because we're always on one side or the other.

59
00:07:07,954 --> 00:07:08,035
Hmm?

60
00:07:10,293 --> 00:07:18,442
Now, when it comes to right effort in daily life, that right effort is, I mean, there's obviously some form of achieving there.

61
00:07:18,682 --> 00:07:20,483
Like if you're at work, you've got to do a job.

62
00:07:20,524 --> 00:07:22,665
If you're at home, you've got to do this and that.

63
00:07:23,226 --> 00:07:25,709
So, the achieving isn't the problem.

64
00:07:25,750 --> 00:07:30,894
The problem is, or if there is a problem, the problem is your intention, you see.

65
00:07:31,134 --> 00:07:32,276
What is your intention?

66
00:07:33,016 --> 00:07:39,303
So, this is where we begin to develop our personalities and our characters.

67
00:07:39,891 --> 00:07:45,122
It's interesting that right there within the Buddha's eightfold path you have right livelihood.

68
00:07:45,862 --> 00:07:51,733
So he's saying that what you do in society is of kernel importance to your spiritual life.

69
00:07:52,495 --> 00:08:02,473
Now if you're doing a job simply to get on, simply for status, simply for money and all that sort of stuff,

70
00:08:02,774 --> 00:08:10,105
then obviously those intentions are going to drive you in a way which create what we know these days as stress.

71
00:08:11,067 --> 00:08:20,682
But if your intention is service, you see, if you take your attention to service, then there's a very different feel to what you do.

72
00:08:21,370 --> 00:08:31,158
That doesn't mean to say that you can't ask for proper wages and that you can't go for a job which has high status but which you feel you can do, see?

73
00:08:31,579 --> 00:08:37,123
But it's the intention which is going to create either an internal state of stress or not.

74
00:08:37,943 --> 00:08:46,912
Now, when you put right effort into your work, this is obviously to do with mindfulness, right?

75
00:08:46,932 --> 00:08:50,955
Which is one of these buzzwords that you see these days, you know, mindfulness and stress, we've got mindfulness.

76
00:08:51,711 --> 00:08:52,692
Mindfulness is all over the place.

77
00:08:53,354 --> 00:08:58,522
So this mindfulness is just doing what you're doing.

78
00:08:59,644 --> 00:09:04,009
In Zen, they say, you know, when you wash the pots, just wash the pots.

79
00:09:04,070 --> 00:09:07,576
It's one of these little famous phrases.

80
00:09:07,596 --> 00:09:11,480
And there was a case of a Zen master who would say this sort of thing.

81
00:09:11,961 --> 00:09:16,227
And he was having breakfast and he was eating his breakfast and reading a newspaper.

82
00:09:17,029 --> 00:09:20,654
So one of his students said to him, Roshi, I

